Previously, we introduced the Shared Kernel as a small, curated set of concepts shared identically across all bounded contexts. We said it was “not a dumping ground.” But what does that actually mean in practice?
Here’s what most Angular teams’ shared modules look like after 18 months:
shared/
├── components/
│ ├── button.component.ts ✅ Fine
│ ├── modal.component.ts ✅ Fine
│ ├── product-card.component.ts ❌ Belongs in Catalog context
│ └── order-summary.component.ts ❌ Belongs in Orders context
├── services/
│ ├── auth.service.ts ⚠️ Maybe its own context
│ ├── cart.service.ts ❌ Belongs in Cart context
│ └── analytics.service.ts ⚠️ Cross-cutting, needs thought
├── models/
│ ├── product.model.ts ❌ Should live in Catalog
│ ├── user.model.ts ⚠️ Maybe shared, maybe not
│ └── address.model.ts ✅ Truly shared
├── utils/
│ ├── format-price.ts ⚠️ Should be Money.format()
│ ├── date-helpers.ts ✅ Fine if truly generic
│ └── string-utils.ts ✅ Fine
└── pipes/
├── money-format.pipe.ts ✅ Fine (shared-kernel)
└── order-status.pipe.ts ❌ Belongs in Orders contextThe mess accumulates because “shared” is conflated with “used in more than one place.” That’s the wrong criterion. The right criterion is: does this concept mean exactly the same thing in every context that uses it, with no exceptions and no context-specific extensions?

What Belongs in the Shared Kernel: The Four Tests
A concept earns its place in the Shared Kernel only if it passes all four tests:
Test 1: Identical Semantics Across All Contexts
Money in the Cart context means exactly the same thing as Money in the Checkout context and the Orders context. There are no "Cart-specific money rules." It's just money — an amount and a currency.
Contrast with Product: the Catalog context needs variants, reviews, and stock counts. The Cart context only needs a name, variant ID, and unit price snapshot. The Orders context needs a frozen name and the price paid. Product fails Test 1 — it means different things in different contexts.
Test 2: No Context-Specific Extensions
A Shared Kernel type should never be subclassed or duck-typed per context. If you find yourself writing CatalogMoney or CartAddress to add context-specific behaviour, the base type doesn't belong in the Shared Kernel.
Test 3: Changing It Requires Coordinating All Contexts
This is the key DDD definition: the Shared Kernel is code that, if changed, requires every team (or context owner) to update their code at the same time. It’s a deliberate coupling — justified only because the concept is genuinely universal.
If changing Money only requires updating one context, it probably belongs in that context.
Test 4: It Has No Dependencies on Any Bounded Context
The Shared Kernel cannot import from CatalogModule, CartModule, or any context module. It is depended upon — it does not depend. Any dependency in that direction is a design smell.

ShopFlow’s Shared Kernel: The Full Picture
Here’s everything that legitimately belongs in ShopFlow’s Shared Kernel, and the reasoning for each:
shared-kernel/
├── value-objects/
│ ├── money.value-object.ts
│ ├── email.value-object.ts
│ ├── address.value-object.ts
│ ├── phone-number.value-object.ts
│ ├── date-range.value-object.ts
│ └── ids/
│ ├── typed-id.base.ts
│ ├── product-id.ts
│ ├── cart-id.ts
│ ├── order-id.ts
│ ├── customer-id.ts
│ ├── coupon-id.ts
│ └── cart-item-id.ts
├── errors/
│ ├── domain-error.ts
│ ├── application-error.ts
│ ├── validation-error.ts
│ └── http-error.mapper.ts
├── result.ts
├── entity.base.ts
├── domain-event-bus.ts
├── pipes/
│ ├── money-format.pipe.ts
│ └── date-format.pipe.ts
├── components/
│ ├── button/
│ ├── input/
│ ├── modal/
│ └── spinner/
└── index.tsNotice what is NOT here:

• No domain models from any context

• No API services

• No context-specific components (no product cards, no cart drawers)

• No routing

• No state (no NgRx reducers or selectors)

The ID Hierarchy: A Shared Kernel Jewel
The typed ID system deserves a full treatment. IDs are the bridge between contexts — they are genuinely shared, while the entities they identify are not.
// shared-kernel/value-objects/ids/typed-id.base.ts
/**
* Base for all domain IDs.
* Using a brand pattern to make IDs nominally typed - not just string aliases.
*/
export abstract class TypedId {
// The '#' makes this a true private field (not just TS-private)
readonly #value: string;
protected constructor(value: string) {
const trimmed = value?.trim();
if (!trimmed || trimmed.length === 0) {
throw new Error(`${this.constructor.name} cannot be empty or whitespace`);
}
if (trimmed.length > 128) {
throw new Error(`${this.constructor.name} cannot exceed 128 characters`);
}
this.#value = trimmed;
}
get value(): string {
return this.#value;
}
equals(other: this): boolean {
return this.#value === other.#value;
}
toString(): string {
return this.#value;
}
toJSON(): string {
return this.#value;
}
}// shared-kernel/value-objects/ids/product-id.ts
export class ProductId extends TypedId {
static generate(): ProductId {
return new ProductId(crypto.randomUUID());
}
static fromString(value: string): ProductId {
return new ProductId(value);
}
}
// All other IDs follow the same pattern:
export class CartId extends TypedId {
static generate(): CartId { return new CartId(crypto.randomUUID()); }
}
export class OrderId extends TypedId {
static generate(): OrderId { return new OrderId(crypto.randomUUID()); }
}
export class CustomerId extends TypedId {
static generate(): CustomerId { return new CustomerId(crypto.randomUUID()); }
}
export class CartItemId extends TypedId {
static generate(): CartItemId { return new CartItemId(crypto.randomUUID()); }
}
Why does this belong in the Shared Kernel? Because ProductId is referenced by multiple contexts:

• The Catalog context creates and owns ProductId

• The Cart context stores ProductId references in CartItem

• The Orders context stores ProductId references in LineItem
The ID is the cross-context reference. The entities it identifies live in their own contexts.

Address: A Richer Shared Kernel Example
Address is one of the most legitimately shared concepts across ShopFlow:

• Checkout uses it as the shipping/billing destination for a new order

• Profile stores saved addresses for a customer

• Orders records the delivery address at time of placement
And it means the same thing in all three: a physical location with street, city, postcode, country.
// shared-kernel/value-objects/address.value-object.ts
export type CountryCode = 'DE' | 'AT' | 'CH' | 'FR' | 'GB' | 'US' | 'NL' | 'BE';
const COUNTRY_NAMES: Record<CountryCode, string> = {
DE: 'Germany', AT: 'Austria', CH: 'Switzerland',
FR: 'France', GB: 'United Kingdom', US: 'United States',
NL: 'Netherlands', BE: 'Belgium',
};
export interface AddressProps {
line1: string;
line2?: string;
city: string;
postcode: string;
countryCode: CountryCode;
state?: string;
}
export class Address {
readonly line1: string;
readonly line2: string | undefined;
readonly city: string;
readonly postcode: string;
readonly countryCode: CountryCode;
readonly state: string | undefined;
constructor(props: AddressProps) {
Address.validate(props);
this.line1 = props.line1.trim();
this.line2 = props.line2?.trim() || undefined;
this.city = props.city.trim();
this.postcode = Address.normalizePostcode(props.postcode, props.countryCode);
this.countryCode = props.countryCode;
this.state = props.state?.trim() || undefined;
}
get countryName(): string {
return COUNTRY_NAMES[this.countryCode];
}
get isUK(): boolean { return this.countryCode === 'GB'; }
get isUS(): boolean { return this.countryCode === 'US'; }
get requiresState(): boolean { return this.isUS; }
/**
* Formats address for display in the selected locale format.
*/
format(style: 'inline' | 'multiline' = 'multiline'): string {
const parts = [
this.line1,
this.line2,
this.city,
this.state,
this.postcode,
this.countryName,
].filter(Boolean) as string[];
return style === 'inline'
? parts.join(', ')
: parts.join('\n');
}
/**
* Returns a new Address with updated fields - immutably.
*/
with(changes: Partial<AddressProps>): Address {
return new Address({
line1: this.line1,
line2: this.line2,
city: this.city,
postcode: this.postcode,
countryCode: this.countryCode,
state: this.state,
...changes,
});
}
equals(other: Address): boolean {
return (
this.line1 === other.line1 &&
this.line2 === other.line2 &&
this.city === other.city &&
this.postcode === other.postcode &&
this.countryCode === other.countryCode &&
this.state === other.state
);
}
toJSON(): AddressProps {
return {
line1: this.line1,
line2: this.line2,
city: this.city,
postcode: this.postcode,
countryCode: this.countryCode,
state: this.state,
};
}
static fromJSON(props: AddressProps): Address {
return new Address(props);
}
private static validate(props: AddressProps): void {
if (!props.line1?.trim()) throw new Error('Address line 1 is required');
if (!props.city?.trim()) throw new Error('City is required');
if (!props.postcode?.trim()) throw new Error('Postcode is required');
if (!COUNTRY_NAMES[props.countryCode]) {
throw new Error(`Unsupported country code: ${props.countryCode}`);
}
if (props.countryCode === 'US' && !props.state?.trim()) {
throw new Error('State is required for US addresses');
}
}
private static normalizePostcode(postcode: string, country: CountryCode): string {
const cleaned = postcode.trim().toUpperCase().replace(/\s+/g, ' ');
if (country === 'GB') {
// UK postcodes: "SW1A 1AA" - insert space if missing
return cleaned.replace(/^([A-Z]{1,2}\d{1,2}[A-Z]?)(\d[A-Z]{2})$/, '$1 $2');
}
return cleaned;
}
}
The DateRange Value Object — Shared Kernel Candidate
Promotions, coupons, and shipment windows all use date ranges. It belongs in the Shared Kernel:
typescript
// shared-kernel/value-objects/date-range.value-object.ts
export class DateRange {
readonly start: Date;
readonly end: Date;
constructor(start: Date, end: Date) {
if (start >= end) {
throw new Error(`DateRange start must be before end. Got: ${start.toISOString()} – ${end.toISOString()}`);
}
this.start = new Date(start);
this.end = new Date(end);
}
get durationInDays(): number {
return Math.ceil((this.end.getTime() - this.start.getTime()) / (1000 * 60 * 60 * 24));
}
contains(date: Date): boolean {
return date >= this.start && date <= this.end;
}
get isActive(): boolean {
return this.contains(new Date());
}
get isExpired(): boolean {
return new Date() > this.end;
}
get isUpcoming(): boolean {
return new Date() < this.start;
}
overlaps(other: DateRange): boolean {
return this.start < other.end && this.end > other.start;
}
equals(other: DateRange): boolean {
return (
this.start.getTime() === other.start.getTime() &&
this.end.getTime() === other.end.getTime()
);
}
toJSON(): { start: string; end: string } {
return {
start: this.start.toISOString(),
end: this.end.toISOString(),
};
}
static fromJSON(json: { start: string; end: string }): DateRange {
return new DateRange(new Date(json.start), new Date(json.end));
}
}
The Shared Kernel Public API: index.ts
The Shared Kernel’s barrel file is its contract with every bounded context. It must be explicit and minimal — nothing leaks in accidentally:
typescript
// shared-kernel/index.ts
// Value Objects
export { Money } from './value-objects/money.value-object';
export type { CurrencyCode } from './value-objects/money.value-object';
export { Email } from './value-objects/email.value-object';
export { Address } from './value-objects/address.value-object';
export type { AddressProps, CountryCode } from './value-objects/address.value-object';
export { DateRange } from './value-objects/date-range.value-object';
export { PhoneNumber } from './value-objects/phone-number.value-object';
// IDs
export { ProductId } from './value-objects/ids/product-id';
export { CartId } from './value-objects/ids/cart-id';
export { CartItemId } from './value-objects/ids/cart-item-id';
export { OrderId } from './value-objects/ids/order-id';
export { CustomerId } from './value-objects/ids/customer-id'
